# **Information Visualization**

**Data abstraction** is the reduction of a particular body of **data** to a simplified representation of the whole.
**Abstraction**, in general, is the process of taking away or removing characteristics from something in order to reduce it to a set of essential characteristics

**Data transformation** in visualization - Visualizing data is not only about <b>*how*</b> to visualize data but also <b>*what*</b> information to visualize.
<br>
## Visual Encoding
<br>
**Visual Encoding** \- The strategy/rules used to transform data into graphical representations
A set of mappings between:

* data items <-> visual marks
* data attributes <-> visual channels

<br>
### **Attribute Types**

* **Categorical** \- a category \(vehicle type\, product type\)
* **Ordinal** \- can be ordered \(order ID\, box size\)
* **Quantitative** \- a value that you can perform arithmetic on \(profit\, height\)
* **Temporal** \- time \(seconds\)
* **Cyclic** \- cycles \(day of week\)
* **Spatial** \- area or coordinates like a map \(longitude\, latitude\)
* **Hierarchal** \- based on a hierarchy \(manager\, employees\)

<br>
### Data Transformation/Aggregation
<br>
Part of the design process. Most projects require you to think cratively about how transformation may lead to better communication and understanding.

most of the time there will be an intermediary step to **Aggregate** the data - some common functions: SUM, MAX, MIN, AVG, MEDIAN, STDDEV
When dealing with hierarchical attributes, data aggregation can be used to generate visualizations at different resolutions/levels.
<br>
1. Select and transform the data
2. Choose and design the representation

<br>
**Common/useful transformations**

* **Time and date aggregation** \- different resolutions of data: seconds\, minutes\, hours\, days\.\.\.
* **Spatial aggregation** \- zip code\, county\, state\.\.\.
* **Spatial Geo coding** \- go from name to coords \(lat\, lng\) or vice versa
* **Quantitative to Ordinal transform** (Binning) - taking a Q value and transforming it into an O (restaurant inspection Ordinal score B from a Quantitative score of 80)
* **Rescaling/re-expression** \- Normalization \(scale from min/max\)
    * normalize from 0 to 1 or -1 to 1 etc.
    * Taking a Q value to a percentage
    * Average Q values

<br>
### **Graph Types**

* **Bar chart** \- visualize how a quantity distributes across a set of categories \[C/O \+ Q\]
* **Line chart** \- visualize how a quantity chages in relation to another quantity \(typically time\) \[T \+ Q\]
* **Scatter plot** \- visualize how a quantity relates to another quantity \[Q \+ Q\]
* **Matrix** \- visualize how a quantity distributes across two categories \[C/O \+ C/O \+ Q\]
* **Symbol map** \- visualize how a quantity distributes across two spatial coordinates \[S \+ Q\]

<br>
* **Slope chart** \- similar to the scatter plot\, 2 parallel axis\, every item can be represented by a line connecting 2 axis \(baseball teams left side wins/losses\, right side total salary\)
* Stacked bar chart

<br>
### 2+ Attributes

* **Bar chart** \- stacked vs grouped
    * stacked - good when main question is regarding the proportions of values within each category
    * grouped - better when the goal is to compare every single value one to another
* **Line chart** \- separate lines\, series\, stacked
    * separate lines - good to compare values
    * series - good for reading individual values over time
    * stacked - values are stacked good if the only question is proportion of values over time
* **Scatter plots + faceting** \- use colors and/or size of the dots for a total of 4 attributes \(plus x and y axis\)\. However it can get hard to read at that point
    * faceted (small multiples) - grouped side by side with a legend at the end

Faceting (small multiples) can be applied to any other graph:

1. select one categorical or ordinal attribute
2. create as many sets as the number of values
3. create one plot for each value

<br>
**Visualization main terms:**

1. Its basic graphical components
2. mapping strategy between data and graphics

<br>
## Marks + Channels
<br>
2 main components of visualizations
**Marks** are the visual objects that *represent* data items
**Channels** are the visual properties that *encode* the properties of the data items or data attributes

**Marks:**

* **Points** \- common for scatter plots\. Every dot represents a data item its position represents 2 values \(usually lat\, lng\)\. Also on maps
* **Bars** \- common for bar charts\. X position is a category or ordinal value and the height is another value\. Can be vertical or horizontal
* **Lines** \- very versitile\. Used in line chart to show something evolving over time\. Also for node diagrams \(nodes connected by lines\) showing relationships between nodes\. Also trees
* **Areas** \- can be used on a scatter plot as circles of different sizes\. On maps with different county or region category \( or using size to represent a quantitative value\)\. Also tree map chart as rectangles of data\.

**Channels:**

* **Position** \- for a scatter the X and Y position are indentifying the value of two attributes\. Bar chart\, the X position identifies the category\. Network diagram for nodes the position is meaningful\. Basically it just identifies the position of the graphical marks\.
* **Size** (length, width, slope) - distinguish between *1D* size and *2D* size.
    * *1D* is bar charts the length is encoding quantitive information. in Lines we can have different thickness width (like in a node diagram to represent network bandwidth.
    * *2D* is bubbles in a bubble chart can have different sizes.
* **Angle** and **Slope** \- in line chart dots are connected by lines and the slope of the line is meaningful \(if X is temporal values then the slope represents rate of change\.\) Another is pie chart the segment angles represent the proportion of the value\.
* **Color** (intensity and hue) - Described as more than one channel. Hue is the name of the color (red, green, blue)  good for encoding categorical information. Intensity is the brightness and good for encoding quantitative information. In pretty much every type of visualization. Very powerful and easy to misuse.
* **Shape and Texture** \- in scatter plot different shapes can represent different categories\. in bars the texture can identify different categories like shading in different directions\.

## Graphical Decoding
<br>
**Graphical Decoding** \- Opposite of encoding\, reverse engineer the viz to analyze the graphical representations\.

1. Indentify explicitly what the graphical components are. identify *marks* and what data items they represent. identify *channels* and what data attributes do they represent.
2. Identify what the mapping rules are.

![Screen Shot 2020-08-27 at 8.46.31 PM.png](data:image/png;base64,)
<br>
> showing medalists in the last 116 years. Olympic sprinter. Companing performance of Usain vs all
> There are a number of *points* and the points are *positioned* in a scatter plot. on X axis is the distance from Usain and Y axis is years (*temporal*)
> The marks are *points*. The *points* represent the medal of the runner
> The channels (3) are X *position* Y *position* and *color*.
> X encodes distance from Usain
> Y encodes time
> Color encodes the type of medal

<br>
**Visual Channels** \- Graphical properties one can use to represent information visually

**How do you know how good the encoding is**? Two principles:

1. **Expressiveness** \- \(*What* can be expressed)
    * Type of information that can (or cannot) be expressed with a channel
        * *nominal* \- categories
        * *ordinal* \- rank order or survey scales \(medium\, high\, very high\)
        * *Interval* \- \(quantitative\) percent or temperature
        * *Ratio* \- \(quantitative\) weight\, height
    * **Quantity** \- position\, size \(1d and 2d\)\, slope\, angle\, color intensity
    * **Order** \- position\, texture/density\, color intensity
    * **Categories** \- position\, color hue\, shape or symbols
    * The visual representation should represent all and only the relationships that exist in the data. Ordered data should not appear as unordered and vice versa. Example - having categorical data on the X axis of a line chart doesn't make sense. Example - a diverging color map (a matrix of 2 categorical with each cell colored by a quantitative value each diverging up or down from 0) using a non diverging scale like cuisine score from 0-100.
2. [**Effectiveness**](#effectiveness2) \- \(*How well* it can be expressed) The relevance of the information should match the effectiveness of the channel. Represent important information with more effective channels. Ex - 2 bars of different color but equal length - try to determine how much bigger B is than A. You can't, the color has no effect, length would be a more effective channel to use. different channels convey quantitative information (ex. magnitude), more or less effectively.

Magnitude (*Quantitative*) channels: *Ordered* attributes **Effectiveness** ranked:

1. *Position* on a common scale
2. *Position* on unaligned scale
3. *Length* (1D size)
4. *Slope* (tilt/angle)
5. *Area* (2D size)
6. *Color* luminance
7. *Color* saturation

Identity channels: *Categorical* attributes **Effectiveness** ranked:

1. Spatial region (*position*)
2. *Color* hue
3. *Shape* or *Texture*

> A good example: [http://www.perceptualedge.com/images/example20solution\_large.jpg](http://www.perceptualedge.com/images/example20solution_large.jpg)

<br>
<br>
**Contextual components:**

* **Legends, labels, annotations** \- enable interpretations of graphical elements\. Ex\. a heat map with labels in the rows and columns and a legend with the color hue\. Ex\. labels on a line chart for time\.
    * **Annotations** guide attention to and explain patterns of interest. Help the reader to interpret the data.
* **Axes, grids, reference lines** \- enable value reading and comparison\. Grid helps you compare 2 values to give a frame of reference\. Reference line helps to show average or a trend over time\.

## Applied Perception of Visualization
<br>
How humans perceive information (cognitive processing). The *effectiveness* of a visualization is decided by visual perception. Visual perception follows specific rules derived from *how the brain works*. knowledge of visual perception is useful because it helps you as a designer to figure out what is effective and what is not effective.

**Space of solutions:**

1. Start from good enough
2. Implrove on initial solution

Accomplishing a *task*: What is really important is to keep in mind that you can only say that the visualization is better than another when you talk about a specific goal or *task* that somebody needs to accomplish.
<br>
### Human Visual Processing System
<br>
**The Eye: Cornea, Pupil, Retina**

* **Pupil** lets light (light, and the reflections of light off of surfaces) in.
* **Cornea** reflects the light around to the back of the eye.
* **Retina** on the back of the eye, (full of photo receptors) receives the light and is connected to the optic nerve.
    * **Rods** \- low light conditions
    * **Cones** \- normal conditions
    * The **Fovea** \- size of a thumbnail at arm length it is very high resolution \(1/10 of a pixel\) compared to rest of the retina \(peripheral\)

> Filter of information as it enters the eye/brain:
> ==> Light ==> Eye ==> stage 1 FEATURES > stage 2 PATTERNS > stage 3 OBJECTS

<br>
Tons of information constantly comes in but very limited information is actually stored by stage 3. Only about 5-7 Objects (or chunks of information). Lossy process!

**Saccadic eye movement** \- we move our eyes extrememely fast to look for information we need\. While moving the image is suppressed and then the image is reconstructed in the brain\.

**inattentional blindness** \- Its easy to be blind to very big changes if we do not attend to the visual information that changes\. Information retained in memory depends on attention\. As a visualization designer you have to be aware of how design choices influence the viewers attention\.

<br>
**Visual Queries** \- Acts of attention driving out eye\-movements to find the information we need to accomplish a task\. The ways the eyes are moving to extract info\. Example \- looking at the subway map to find out how to go from point A to point B\. Visual queries to see which trains get you there the fastest\. First see if the 2 locations share the same color line\, if not see where they can connect the 2 line colors\.
<br>
> Explicitly identify the tasks and visual queries your visualization is meant to help accomplish. Use the visual queries paradigm to verify how easy or hard it is to find an answer.

**Neurons** respond to different types of properties: Form, Color, Orientation, Motion, Depth, and Sound. Some things we can process very efficiently some not so much as when we have preattentive features.

<br>
**"Eyes Beat Memory"** Think about scrolling something or zooming in to something or panning an image, every time we do that, we are doing something that is much slower than moving our eyes. So, in general, we should try as much as possible to visualize as much information in one picture without scrolling, zooming or panning if we want to make sure that our readers or users are able to compare or detect pieces of information from different locations in the image.

making tasks and visual queries explicit in your design process is a very useful tool. In particular, is very important for you to ask yourself, what are the questions that the viewer has? What are the visual queries that are associated to these questions?
<br>
> Every viz can be described as a mapping between data properties to visual properties

<br>
Symbols -> Objects of interest
Bar       ->  Category

Graphical properties -> Object properties
<br>
### <a name="effectiveness2">Effectiveness of Visual Channels</a>
<br>
**Accuracy** \- How well can you estimate magnitudes

* How accurate a channel can express quantitative information. *Psychophysics* is a branch of physics and psycology that studies the relationship between the physical intensity of a signal and the perceived sensation from a human. It always follows a power law. Some follow over or under estimation
    * Physical Shock 1 : 3.5
    * Saturation 1 : 1.7
    * Length 1 : 1
    * Area: 1 : 0.7
    * Depth 1 : 0.67
    * Brightness 1 : 0.5
* **Channels** (best to worst) *Position* > *Length* and *Angle* > *Area* for magnitude estimation and comparison
* Prioritize high rank channels (within reason) and do not expect precise judgements from low rank channels
* If you need to represent a lot of information (*scaling*) then you can use some less accurate channels like using a heatmap on a lot of categories and color intensity

**Discriminibility** \- how many distinct values can you identify

* If you have too many areas or too many colors for example you wont be able to tell the difference between them
* Depends on channel properties (same ranking as accuracy) spatial arrangement, size, and cardinality
    * Effect of **Spatial** arrangement - A series of bubbles of different sizes in a line (easy to distiin gush size) or a random position (harder to distinguish). Colors arranged in a grid (easy) arranged spread out and random (harder).
    * Effect of **Size** \- A scatter plot the *marks* are colored by category smaller *marks* are hard to distingush bigger dots are easier.
    * Effect of **Cardinality** \- How many values you want to represent\. For colors less is easier more is harder
* Do not overestimnate the number of distinct values the viewer can perceive/discriminate.
* **Low Discriminibility** \- A scatterplot with a lot \(20\) colored categories is hard to read and has *low Discriminibility.* The problem is trying to encode *categorical* attributes with high *cardinality*. Here are 3 **solutions** for that:
    * **Grouping** \- group similair categories together and separate
    * **Filtering** \- filter down to what you need \(4\-6 categoreis\) top 5 strategy
    * **Faceting** \- change the *channel* you are encoding the *categorical* attributes from *color* to *position* (have them side by side as multiple charts).

**Salience** (pop-out) - how easy is it to single out (attract attention to) information by using channels

* Wheres waldo is low *salience*. Color has higher salience than shape
* **Preattentive Processing** \- Human vision works in a way where some visual features can be detected extremely fast \(less than \~250ms\)\. Processed by the parallel low\-level visual system\. You can see a red dot in a sea of blue dots very fast/easily
* **Non-Preattentive Features** \- Juncture \(is there a junction between\)\, Parallelism \(how parallel are 2 lines\)\. Most of the time multiple channels are *not* preattentive.
    * **Conjunctive Search** \- requires searching for two features at the same time\.
    * Some channels are stronger than others. Color is stronger than size. Size is *asymmetric* though - larger bubbles stand out more and smaller bubbles
* Important to be mindful of how you are directing the viewers attention.
* If you have a grouped line chart where some values are all close to zero and 2 arent, you can gray out those lower unchanging values for higher *salience*. This offloads the cognitive effort to understand what to attend to.
* Use color sparingly. learn to love gray shades.

**Separability** \- amount of interference between channels \(color and size\) how do they interact

* separating color is easy, shapes, or width and height is not.
* Position and color are highly seperable so it is easy to focus on one without any interference from the other.
* Use *integral* dimensions when holistic reading is needed. holistic meaning you want your viewer to react to the 2+ dimensions as one single unit.
    * Example showing 400 people body mass index each is a circle and then the height is mapped to the height of the elipse and weight to the width of the elipse. It is perceived as one feature of the data. These are *integral* dimensions
* Use *separable* dimensions when the viewer to focus on one single dimension at the time and then to the other.

**Grouping** \- how easy is it to see pattern formation

* **Gestalt laws of grouping** \- visualization is about pattern identification\. But what makes patterns emerge?
* Order (lowest to heighest): Similarity > Proximity > Enclosure & Connection
    * **Proximity** \- If objects positioned in proximity they are perceived as a group\. On a scatter plot dots *clustered* around one value (a *cluster*).
    * **Similarity** \- If objects share a visual property they are a group\. Some dots are gray some are black\, or some are an X and some are an O\. \(Color and shape\)\.
    * **Connection** \- If objects are connected they are a group\. A line between 2 squares groups them regardes of their color \(over ruling the law of similarity\)\.
    * **Enclosure** \- If objects enclosed by a contour are a group\. A circle or some kind of box bordering objects groups them\. Bubble sets
    * **Closure** \- If there are gaps in open structures they are perceived as closed if it makes sense\. Negative space can look like a group
    * **Continuity** \- If objects are aligned along a shape or line they are perceived as a group even if there are some gaps in between\. Alignment is very powerful\.

## Visualizing data with color
<br>
Color is an extremely powerful channel. It is useful for:

1. **Patterns** \- Encoding quantitative values with color to visualize the patterns
2. **Labeling** \- Label data to distinguish between a set of predefined categories
3. **Highlighting** \- HIghlight visual elements to draw attention to specific objects

### **Color Perception**
<br>
Retina, rods, cones. the optic nerve connects to the brain and is a blind spot. Rods have low light low resolution. Cones have normal light and high resolution. There are 3 types of cones (trichromacy):

* Short wavelength - Red
* Medium wavelength - Green
* Long wavelength - Blue

**Color Opponent Process Theory** - We do not perceive color in terms of amount of RGB. The visual cortex combines those to generate color perception we process it as:

1. Red-Green
2. Blue-Yellow
3. Black-White (luminance)

<br>

### Color Specification
<br>
Every color can be expressed as the sum of three colors. In a 3D space. gamut is the whole set of colors that can be produced. Not all color spaces can produce all the possible colors. Color spaces define in terms the amount red, green, blue. Color spaces:

* **RGB** \- Red Green Blue \- common in digital devices\. Pixels in an LCD screen\. Color cube\. 0 to 1 all 1 is white\. RGB is not perceptually uniform\. Not very intuitive\. It is tough to for example use yellow and then get different intensities of yellow
